Step 1: Express $\tan^2 x$ and $\cot^2 x$ in terms of $\sin^2 x$ and $\cos^2 x$.
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{1 - \tan^2 x} + \frac{1}{1 - \cot^2 x} &= \frac{1}{1 - \sin^2 x/\cos^2 x} + \frac{1}{1 - \cos^2 x/\sin^2 x}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Multiply both numerators and denominators by $\cos^2 x$ and $\sin^2 x$, respectively.
$$\begin{align*}
&= \frac{\cos^2 x}{\cos^2 x - \sin^2 x} + \frac{\sin^2 x}{\sin^2 x - \cos^2 x}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Combine the fractions by subtracting the second fraction from the first.
$$\begin{align*}
&= \frac{\cos^2 x}{\cos^2 x - \sin^2 x} - \frac{\sin^2 x}{\cos^2 x - \sin^2 x}
\end{align*}$$

Step 4: Factor out the common denominator and simplify.
$$\begin{align*}
&= \frac{\cos^2 x - \sin^2 x}{\cos^2 x - \sin^2 x} = 1
\end{align*}$$

